<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Pinus attenuata </i>is a conifer that rapidly attains a height of 12 m. The typical lifespan of <i>P. attenuata </i>is relatively short, with some trees reaching maximum ages of 75-100 years; in a typical 60- to 100-year-old stand, however, over half the pines will be dead. Mature trees have multiple trunks with thin bark. Trees begin cone production by 10 years of age. The cones, attached in whorls to the trunk and branches, are persistent and serotinous. Fire initiates reproduction; cones gradually open and release seeds after high temperatures vaporize the resin. Birds, gravity, and wind disperse the released seeds, which remain viable in the soil for over 25 years. Seedlings require bare mineral soil for seedling establishment (Griffin and Critchfield 1972, Howard 1992g). <br/>
<br/>
Stands of <i>P. attenuata </i>typically occur on nutrient-deficient soils with and without dense understories (Minnich 2007). They tend to vary regionally in size and occurrence: the trees in many stands are dense, forming closed canopies; in others, trees are scattered and canopies are open. Associated vegetation is often chaparral, but in some regions, the surrounding vegetation includes coniferous forests, montane chaparral, and oak woodlands. Individual <i>P. attenuata </i>trees often emerge through shrub canopies in stands of many chaparral alliances. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
