<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">Fires kill <i>Pinus attenuata </i>trees; it is an obligate fire species with a strict closed-cone habit. This adaptation, along with the general absence of animal agents that might open cones, leaves the species dependent on stand-replacing crown fire for reproduction. Fire creates conditions favorable for seed germination and seedling recruitment. Fire also favors soil erosion especially on infertile, serpentine substrates, in which few species can grow with <i>P. attenuata </i>after fire. Fire-opened cones remain attached to down and standing-dead trees, and release seeds; seedlings establish for several years after a fire (Howard 1992g).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
			<td>Truncated medium (20-50 years)
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
