    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Ac, Af, Aj-k). Small groves and more-extensive stands in the Santa Cruz Mountains are closely associated with chaparral types. Stands in Santa Barbara Co. are planted (Griffin and Critchfield 1972). Groves are rare and local in the East Bay Hills; they are associated with chaparral on nutrient-deficient marine sediments.</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ac, Ae). Stands are extensive in the northern Diablo Ranges and Santa Lucia Mountains on and off serpentine substrates.</li>
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Aa-f, Ai-m, Aq-r, Au). Stands throughout the section occur at low and montane elevations; they are most extensive on the serpentine substrates in the Smith River drainage, and in the Scott Bar and Trinity mountains, including those in Craig’s Creek rRNA, Manzanita Creek RNA, Pearch Creek study area (Cheng 2004), and in the Whiskeytown National Recreation Area (Lee 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Gn). Stands in Timbered Crater RNA (Keeler-Wolf 1990a, see Cheng 2004) cover 55 ha on Quaternary lava flows. <i>Arctostaphylos patula</i> and <i>Ceanothus cordulatus</i> are common shrubs.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ab, Ag, Am). Stands are known in Del Norte Coast Redwoods State Park (Forys pers. communication 2020). Groves in the King Range in Humboldt Co. and in the hills around the Napa Valley are small.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Bb-f). Stands in the section are most extensive north and south of Clear Lake on serpentine and volcanic substrates. Stands at Hale Ridge RNA (Keeler-Wolf 1987c, see Cheng 2004) are on Franciscan sediments.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Interior Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ca). Stands throughout the section on serpentine substrates are similar to those at Frenzel Creek RNA (Keeler-Wolf 1983, see Cheng 2004). Stands off serpentine substrates are dense over <i>Arctostaphylos visida</i> and <i>Ceanothus cuneatus</i> shrubs.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Eg, Ep). Stands cluster in two portions of the section centered in El Dorado and Mariposa Cos. The southern cluster includes stands in Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bf-g). Stands in the San Bernardino Mountains are extensive; those in the Santa Ana Mountains cover only a few ha (Vogl et al. 1988, Klein and Evens 2005, Minnich 2007, Minnich and Everett 2001). The southernmost stands in the Santa Ana Mountains are on gabbro and serpentine (Vogl 1976, Alexander et al. 2007), surrounded by stands of the <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum</i> and <i>Arctostaphylos glandulosa</i> alliances.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Da, Df-h, Dj, Dl). Stands in the central subsections are most extensive east of Mount Shasta, including Mayfield cRNA (Imper 1991b, see Cheng 2004). Stands also occur in the lower-elevation portions of the western subsections.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Isolated stands surrounded by suburban development, as in the East Bay area of the central coast, have particularly problematic fire management issues. </div>
</div>

    

    

